The paper discusses a hardware accelerator for Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) that exploits weight sparsity, per layer precision variability, and dynamic fine-grain precision reduction for activations. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) or Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the reduction of storage, communication, and computation demands, which could fall under the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of Bit-Tactical (TCL), which is a technique for exploiting ineffectual computations in CNNs, which could fall under the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the paper is discussing a practical application of a hardware accelerator, which could also fall under the Architecture (cs.AR) sub-category.
